<div class="body" id="fhbody-175712713">
	
		
	

	
		
		<div id="text-175712713" class="p">
			
		 	
				Apple has <a href="https://www.macrumors.com/2024/12/20/iphone-14-iphone-se-unavailable-in-switzerland/">started pulling</a> its iPhone SE and iPhone 14 models from sale in Switzerland, signaling broader discontinuation across the European Union ahead of new USB-C charging requirements <a href="https://tech.slashdot.org/story/22/12/08/150216/eu-sets-december-28-2024-deadline-for-all-new-phones-to-use-usb-c-for-wired-charging">taking effect December 28</a>.<br> <br>

The devices, which use Apple's proprietary Lightning port, disappeared from Swiss online stores today. Switzerland, while not an EU member, follows EU market rules. Apple-authorized resellers can continue selling existing stock until depleted. A new USB-C compatible iPhone SE is expected in March.<br>
		 	
		</div>

		

		

		
			
		
